---
// The thesis, as a short editorial passage: OSN decouples the social graph from
// the apps that use it. Sets the frame before any feature is named.
---
<section class="px-6 py-24 md:py-32" aria-labelledby="promise-heading">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-[52rem] text-center" data-reveal>
    <p class="font-body text-accent mb-6 text-[0.72rem] font-medium tracking-[0.26em] uppercase">
      Why OSN
    </p>
    <h2
      id="promise-heading"
      class="font-display text-text text-[clamp(1.9rem,4.5vw,3rem)] leading-[1.2] font-bold tracking-[-0.02em]"
    >
      The graph is yours. The apps are guests.
    </h2>
    <p class="font-body text-text-muted mx-auto mt-7 max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8]">
      On most platforms, the company owns your connections — and every app you touch tries to rebuild
      that web from scratch, then keep it. Your relationships end up scattered, duplicated, and
      locked inside products you can&rsquo;t leave.
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-text mt-6 mx-auto max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8]">
      OSN flips that. Your identity and your social graph live with <em>you</em>. Apps opt in to the
      slice you grant them and nothing more. Block someone once and it propagates everywhere — unless
      you decide otherwise.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
